07863nam a22012495i 9783110254310DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20112011gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2011032133  a(OCoLC)840440294  a97831102543107 a10.1515/97831102543102doi  a(DE-B1597)123520  a(OCoLC)776492386  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aP40b.S596 2011 4aP40b.S596 2011eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh0481ua304.23qDE-101222/ger00aSpatial Dimensions of Social Thought /ced. by Thomas W. Schubert, Anne Maass. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (353 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aApplications of Cognitive Linguistics [ACL] ,x1861-4078 ;v180 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSpace provides the stage for our social lives - social thought evolved and developed in a constant interaction with space. The volume demonstrates how this has led to an astonishing intertwining of spatial and social thought. For the first time, research on language comprehension, metaphors, priming, spatial perception, face perception, art history and other fields is brought together to provide an integrative view. This overview confirms that often, metaphors reveal a deeper truth about how our mind uses spatial information to represent social concepts. Yet, the evidence also goes beyond this insight, showing for instance how flexible our mind operates with spatial metaphors, how the peculiarities of our bodies determine the way we assign meaning to space, and how the asymmetry of our brain influences spatial and face perception. Finally, it is revealed that also how we write language - from left to right or from right to left - shapes how we perceive, interpret, and produce horizontal movement and order. The evidence ranges from linguistics to social and spatial perception to neuropsychology, seamlessly integrating such diverse findings as speed in word comprehension, children's depictions of abstract concepts, estimates of the steepness of hills, and archival research on how often Homer Simpson is depicted left or right of Marge. The chapters in this book offer a topology of social cognition and explore the pivotal role language plays in creating links between spatial and social thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aCognitive grammarxSocial aspects. 0aPsycholinguistics. 0aSociolinguistics 0aSociolinguistics. 4aAngewandte Linguistik. 4aKognition. 4aKognitive Linguistik. 4aPsychologie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCognitive Linguistics.  aPsychology.  aSocial Cognition.1 aAgostini, Maria De, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrady, Nuala, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChatterjee, Anjan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChokron, Sylvie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFörster, Jens, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHegarty, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKazandjian, Seta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLemieux, Anthony F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiberman, Nira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaass, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaass, Anne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcManus, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOuellet, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRomán, Antonio, 